{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480759","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480759"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:50:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:50:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"105"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"105","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/105"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.06,0.52,0.1,0.3]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"105"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"27171"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"105","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/105"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"105"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"14098"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"88"},{"type":"tags","id":"176"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"2522"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2654"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3120"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17750"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"27171","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/27171"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old man presents with a 3-day history of cough and purulent sputum production. There is an area of dullness to percussion at the right base of his chest with bronchial breathing. \u0026nbsp;A chest X-ray reveals focal consolidation consistent with the diagnosis of a lobar pneumonia, amounting to his fourth episode of pneumonia in the past three months.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe also reports a 4-month history of back pain, which he refers to as a \u0022constant ache\u0022 that wakes him up at night multiple times. Over this time-frame, he has noticed he is increasingly tired, has drenched his pyjama shirts on multiple occasions and has had an 8 kg weight loss (unintentionally).\u0026nbsp;\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn Examination, there is evidence of periorbital purpura and mild ankle swelling bilaterally. Spinal exam demonstrates tenderness at T4/5 vertebral level.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis blood tests show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 90 (135-180g/L)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMCV: 80 (76-96fL)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be the next most appropriate diagnostic investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["DEXA bone scan","Corrected calcium level","Serum and urine electrophoresis","Mediastinal lymph node biopsy","MRI Spine"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis man\u0027s presentation is consistent with 2 of 4 features from the classic tetrad of multiple myeloma: bone pain, anaemia, renal impairment and hypercalcaemia. This case additionally demonstrates other potential complications inclusive of recurrent infections and amyloidosis (as suggested by the periorbital purpura and oedema), of which the latter can also contribute to renal impairment.  \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMultiple Myeloma represents roughly 10% of all haematological cancers which arise from plasma B cells and for which the median age of diagnosis is 70. Presentations can range from MGUS (monoclonal gammopathy of undetermined significance) to smouldering to overt multiple myeloma. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum and urine electrophoresis\u003C/strong\u003E would most easily help to confirm the  diagnosis of multiple myeloma. It would likely reveal the presence of a monoclonal band which coupled with immunofixation could establish more specifics about the paraprotein e.g. IgA or IgG.  An \u003Cstrong\u003EMRI Spine\u003C/strong\u003E would be an important additional investigation to consider to evaluate for pathological fractures and lytic lesions. An \u003Cstrong\u003Eelevated calcium\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ereduced bone density\u003C/strong\u003E would be consistent with the diagnosis of multiple myeloma, but are not diagnostic of the condition. A \u003Cstrong\u003Emediastinal lymph node biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in this situation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["New onset back pain without specific triggers over 50 always warrants further investigation for a serious aetiology.","Amyloidosis, which can arise as a complication of multiple myeloma, is a multisystemic disease which can manifest in heart failure, nephrotic syndrome, hepatomegaly, macroglossia, periorbital purpura and alzheimer\u0027s disease to name a few."],"references":["Tomlinson, R. Multiple Myeloma: Update approach to management in 2018. AJGP [Internet]. 2018 Aug [cited 2021 June 30];47(8): 526-529. Available from: https://www1.racgp.org.au/getattachment/ba21a7ea-ba44-49a4-9aa8-6979298c65ae/Multiple-myeloma.aspx","Bustamante, JG \u0026 Zaidi, SRH. Amyloidosis. Treasure Island: StatPearls Publishing [Internet]. 2021 Jan- [cited 2021 June 30]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470285/."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"14098"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"105"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"14098","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/14098"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2022-08-27T20:31:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-26T17:41:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"105"}},"content":{"da